2500|$|Conductivity of {{the surface}} affects the {{propagation}} of <b>ground</b> <b>waves,</b> with more conductive surfaces such as sea water providing better propagation. Increasing the conductivity in a surface results in less dissipation. The refractive indices are subject to spatial and temporal changes. Since the ground is not a perfect electrical conductor, <b>ground</b> <b>waves</b> are attenuated as they follow the earth’s surface. [...] The wavefronts initially are vertical, but the ground, acting as a lossy dielectric, causes the wave to tilt forward as it travels. [...] This directs some of the energy into the earth where it is dissipated, so that the signal decreases exponentially.|$|R
